# Lumina Middleware Patterns

## Assigning Middleware via the Model

In Lumina, middleware is assigned directly on the model using `$middleware` and `$middlewareActions` properties -- **not** in controllers or route files.

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\HasFactory;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\SoftDeletes;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HasValidation;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HidableColumns;

class Article extends \Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model
{
    use HasFactory;
    use SoftDeletes;
    use HasValidation;
    use HidableColumns;

    // Applied to ALL actions on this model
    protected $middleware = ['verified'];

    // Applied to specific actions only
    protected $middlewareActions = [
        'store' => ['throttle:5,1'],
        'update' => ['throttle:10,1'],
        'destroy' => ['throttle:3,1'],
    ];
}
```

## Available Actions

The following action names can be used as keys in `$middlewareActions`:

| Action    | HTTP Method | Route                          |
|-----------|-------------|--------------------------------|
| `index`   | GET         | `/api/{org}/{model}`           |
| `store`   | POST        | `/api/{org}/{model}`           |
| `show`    | GET         | `/api/{org}/{model}/{id}`      |
| `update`  | PUT         | `/api/{org}/{model}/{id}`      |
| `destroy` | DELETE      | `/api/{org}/{model}/{id}`      |

## Standard Middleware Structure

Custom middleware follows the standard Laravel middleware pattern:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Http\Middleware;

use Closure;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Symfony\Component\HttpFoundation\Response;

class EnsureEmailVerified
{
    public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next): Response
    {
        if (!$request->user() || !$request->user()->hasVerifiedEmail()) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Your email address is not verified.',
            ], 403);
        }

        return $next($request);
    }
}
```

Register the middleware in `bootstrap/app.php` (Laravel 11+) or `app/Http/Kernel.php` (Laravel 10), then reference it by alias in the model:

```php
// bootstrap/app.php (Laravel 11+)
->withMiddleware(function (Middleware $middleware) {
    $middleware->alias([
        'verified' => \App\Http\Middleware\EnsureEmailVerified::class,
        'subscription' => \App\Http\Middleware\EnsureActiveSubscription::class,
    ]);
})
```

```php
// Then reference by alias in the model
protected $middleware = ['verified'];
protected $middlewareActions = [
    'store' => ['subscription'],
];
```

## Combining Global and Action-Specific Middleware

Both `$middleware` and `$middlewareActions` can be used together. Global middleware runs first, then action-specific middleware:

```php
class Document extends \Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model
{
    // Runs on every action
    protected $middleware = ['auth:sanctum', 'verified'];

    // Additional middleware for specific actions
    protected $middlewareActions = [
        'store' => ['throttle:10,1', 'subscription'],
        'update' => ['throttle:20,1'],
        'destroy' => ['throttle:5,1'],
    ];
}
```

## DON'Ts

- **DO NOT** put authorization logic in middleware. Use Policies for authorization decisions.

```php
// BAD: Auth logic in middleware
public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next): Response
{
    if (!$request->user()->rolesInOrganization()->contains('slug', 'admin')) {
        abort(403); // Wrong! Use a Policy for this.
    }
    return $next($request);
}
```

- **DO NOT** use middleware for data filtering. Use Scopes to control which records a user can see.

```php
// BAD: Data filtering in middleware
public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next): Response
{
    // Wrong! Use a Scope for data visibility.
    $request->merge(['only_published' => true]);
    return $next($request);
}
```

- **DO NOT** register middleware in controller constructors. Lumina does not use controllers for CRUD operations. Always use the model's `$middleware` and `$middlewareActions` properties.

```php
// BAD: Controller-based middleware registration
class ArticleController extends Controller
{
    public function __construct()
    {
        $this->middleware('verified'); // Wrong! Lumina doesn't use controllers.
    }
}
```

- **DO NOT** define middleware directly in route files for Lumina-managed routes. The routes are auto-generated and middleware should come from the model.
